WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.320
Have you ever heard of the Grammar of Graphics?, it's a powerful layer-based framework for

00:00:04.320 --> 00:00:10.560
building data visualizations. First introduced by Leland Wilkinson in 2001, the idea is that

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:16.040
any statistical plot can be broken down into a distinct hierarchy of elements. It was famously

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:22.200
popularized in R via ggplot2, allowing you to build highly customized, elegant graphs

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:28.080
by stacking code layers, defaults layers, scale, coordinates, and facets. ggplot2 also

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:33.480
has a huge ecosystem of packages that can help you create the graph of your dreams.

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:38.320
You can use the same framework across other languages, like PlotName for Python, ggsql

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:43.279
for SQL, and gribouille for Types. What's your go-to plotting library? Let us know in

00:00:43.279 --> 00:00:43.919
the comments.

